ces that created and gave momentum to the phenomenon of life on ice and shows how these preserved blood samples served as the building blocks for biomedicine at the dawn of the genomic age. In an era of vigorous ethical, legal, and cultural debates about genetic privacy and identity, Life on Ice reveals the larger picture—how we got here and the promises and problems involved with finding new uses for cold human blood samples.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aBloodxCryopreservation. 0aCryopreservation of organs, tissues, etc - Moral and ethical aspects. 0aCryopreservation of organs, tissues, etc.xMoral and ethical aspects. 0aFrozen blood. 0aMedical anthropology. 0aMedicinexResearchxHistoryy20th century. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aSTS.  abiobanking.  ablood.  acyropreservation.  aethics.  ahuman biology.  aindigeneity.  ainfrastructure.  asuspended animation.  atemporality.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831107119360 cprintz978022641731840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226448244423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226448244/original  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles